A digital junto club has a lot of benefits too. For one, you can have a more interesting and diverse group, but it’s difficult to ensure quality of members - maybe solved by having a lowish bar for entry but a high bar for staying

I have thought about a digital junto club for a long time. In my mind, the execution always came down to two elements:
1) high quality people - fundamentally a junto club is just a group of people who you want to talk to, who you respect, and can trust. 
2) a shared experience, purpose, or mission - this is pretty trite group dynamics stuff, but I always felt bringing together 8 strangers over zoom could get very awkward without some agenda or structure ahead of time.

I think we would need to decide is it more of a mastermind group, a group for accountability, or more philosophical / pursuit of truth oriented. It could potentially be both, but they have different requirements and design considerations

Run into somewhat similar lines of thought patterns, but I don't think "we would need to decide..." is the most conducive framework. 
imo It would look more like you and a few people you get on with having a private vc over shared interests than the mods creating a #junto channel with a mission statement
@benjlaufer @Jack Gecawich thoughts?

I think it can function similarly to how GZM discord was established, which was that it was organic and adaptable, but also deliberate. There should be some filter (defined by the early members) and a set of abstract goals, but the end doesn’t need to be clear, as the group’s members will overtime define that. 

I do think that having a person or two acting as the guide/curator is good. In the same way that @suds 1. serves to provide some sense of structure (ie. fireside chats) to an otherwise relatively unstructured community and 2. Thinks about the upkeep, maintenance, and values of the group as things evolve, I think that a junto club would benefit from someone having a similar role.
